snippet.textDisplay:
Viral loading will make a difference which is why people who are around it more often get it more seriously.


While mortality is lower for younger demographics, a certain percentage still need to be hospitalized and in ICU. Given how nobody has any immunity to this and it is incredibly contagious, the largest concern is sheer volume of people who are infected. If for example (not accurate numbers) 20% needs to be hospitalized and 10% need to be placed in ICU, when the number of infected reaches a high enough number there isn't enough capacity at hospitals to care for the amount of people who need assistance, which will increase mortality.


Hence the social distancing to slow down people getting it to keep it manageable. The contagiousness and hospitalizations are the largest problems. The flu has a r0 value of 1.3, while the Coronavirus has an estimated r0 value of 2 to 3. That might not seem all that bad, until you take into account the layers of people infected. One person with the flu 10 layers down would have infected roughly 14 people. One person with the Coronavirus 10 layers down would have infected roughly 59,000 people (at a r0 value of 3. a r0 value of 2 would be 1024).
